	title = {AI-Based Framework for Financial Data Mapping and Analysis Using RAG and Transformer Models},
	year = {2025},
	journal = {International Conference on Electrical, Computer, Communications and Mechatronics Engineering, ICECCME 2025},
	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1109/ICECCME64568.2025.11277623},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105031401873?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Victorian Institute of Technology, Dept. of Information Technology and Systems, Sydney, Australia},
	abstract = {Use of Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) for data analysis has gained popularity in recent years. This research aims to develop a robust, AI-assisted open-source framework for mapping and analyzing structured financial data, powered by RAG and fine-tuned transformer models. The system eliminates the need for manually pulling data, running queries, summarizing, and visualizing primary financial metrics such as revenue, net income, return on investment (ROI), and shareholder equity. Using Sentence Transformer Models (STM) and Facebook AI Similarity Search (FAISS), each financial record is encoded into dense vectors for semantic retrieval. When a user asks a natural language question, the system pulls up related records and creates summaries with a Meta AI, Bidirectional and Auto-Regressive Transformers (BART) model. The proposed solution is designed as a modular architecture combining data ingestion, preprocessing, embedding, RAG-based querying, BART summarization, and interactive visualization components (via Plotly and Streamlit). A prototype was developed based on Jupyter Notebook and tested over real financial data acquired from Fintags Pty Limited. It solves problems such as manual data management, inconsistent data and the lag in decision making with a scalable, precise, and easy-to-use tool. It allows business and financial analysts to get contextually relevant insights from large datasets without needing to know how to code. Experimental results show significant gains in analytical efficiency, model interpretability, and business decision support conventional financial analysis techniques. The proposed system demonstrates how AI-powered semantic summarization can replace conventional manual workflows in financial analysis, improving speed, accessibility, and decision-making quality.  © 2025 IEEE.},
