	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033663650?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {School of Computing, Telkom University, Bandung, Indonesia},
	abstract = {Large Language Models (LLMs) show promise for product recommendations but often struggle with specific, up-to-date information. To address this, this paper introduces SARLAR, a smart assistant for laptop recommendations using an agentic Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) system. The main problem is the gap between ambiguous user requests and the technical data structure. We implement and evaluate two methods: a standard agentic architecture and an enhanced version incorporating a”Guidance System” stored in a vector database. The comparative analysis reveals a clear trade-off. The method with the Guidance System achieved a significantly higher accuracy of 96.40% compared to the standard method’s 90.09%. However, this accuracy improvement came at the cost of a 33% increase in token consumption and a 6 seconds longer processing time. A paired t-test shows that the better accuracy is not due to random occurrence but a statistically proven performance improvement. The findings show that while a dynamic guidance system substantially boosts recommendation accuracy, it requires careful consideration of the associated resource costs. While SARLAR is slower because of the multiagent process, it is much easier to maintain than existing methods because we simply update the Vector Database. Therefore, SARLAR is better for businesses where products change often. © 2025 IEEE.},
