	abstract = {With the acceleration of the digital transformation of power systems, substation operation and inspection businesses face challenges such as the high complexity of equipment inspection, strong real-time response requirements, and high dependence on manual labour. Traditional methods rely on fixed processes and manual experience, making it difficult to adapt to dynamic environments and specialised needs. This paper proposes a model-based, collaborative approach to substation operations and inspection, empowered by large models, elevating the Large Language Model (LLM) from a mere "chat tool"to an "autonomous intelligent agent"with planning and execution capabilities. Through the tool-enhanced LLM mechanism, professional numerical calculations, precise identification, and other tools are equipped for the model, expanding its ability to handle specialized tasks in substation operation and inspection; introducing dynamic adaptive workflows, the large model dynamically generates and adjusts business processes according to real-time contexts, achieving highly flexible model operation and collaboration; simultaneously, integrating Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) technology, combining knowledge bases such as equipment ledgers and procedural specifications with the large model, ensuring decision-making accuracy, and optimizing professional models and knowledge bases through operational feedback mechanisms to support continuous learning. The effectiveness of this method has been verified in simulated substation operation and inspection scenarios, significantly improving operational and inspection efficiency and accuracy, and offering a new paradigm for intelligent operation and inspection in the power industry. © 2025 IEEE.},
